('NA000253', 'Rufrae', 'feminine', 'Latin name possibly meaning "red places". From Latin *rufus* "red". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Rufrae is an ancient city in Campania.', 'Rufrae', 'Rufrae', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000254', 'Batulum', 'neuter', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Greek *batylos* meaning "sacred stone". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Batulum appears as an ancient Italian settlement.', 'Batulum', 'Batulum', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000255', 'Celemna', 'feminine', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from pre-Roman substrate. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Celemna appears as an ancient Italian city or region.', 'Celemna', 'Celemna', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000256', 'Abella', 'feminine', 'Latin name possibly meaning "hazelnut place". From Latin *abellana* "hazelnut". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Abella is an ancient city in Campania, famous for its apples and hazelnuts.', 'Abella', 'Abella', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000257', 'Ufens', 'masculine', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from pre-Roman substrate. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Ufens appears as both a river name and a warrior leader.', 'Ufens', 'Ufens', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000258', 'Nersae', 'feminine', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Volscian origins. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Nersae appears as an ancient Italian settlement.', 'Nersae', 'Nersae', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000259', 'Aequiculi', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning "little Aequi". From the Aequi, an ancient Italian people + diminutive suffix. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, the Aequiculi are a people related to the Aequi of central Italy.', 'Aequiculi', 'Aequiculi', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000260', 'Venulus', 'masculine', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Venulus appears as an Italian warrior or messenger sent by Turnus to seek aid from Diomedes.', 'Venulus', 'Venulus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000261', 'Evander', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "good man" or "strong man". From Greek *eu* (*εὖ*) "good, well" + *aner* (*ἀνήρ*), genitive *andros* (*ἀνδρός*) "man". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Evander is the Arcadian king who founded Pallanteum on the site that would become Rome.', 'Εὔανδρος', 'Evander', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000262', 'Cyllene', 'feminine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly pre-Greek. Mountain in Arcadia, birthplace of Hermes. In Greek mythology and Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Cyllene is associated with Arcadian geography and divine presence.', 'Κυλλήνη', 'Cyllene', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000263', 'Pheneus', 'masculine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "bright" or from pre-Greek substrate. Ancient Arcadian city. In Greek mythology and Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Pheneus is an important Arcadian settlement.', 'Φενεός', 'Pheneus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000264', 'Pallas', 'masculine', 'Greek name possibly meaning "youth" or "brandisher". From Greek *pallas* (*Παλλάς*). In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Pallas is the beloved son of King Evander, killed by Turnus. Also the name of a Titan and epithet of Athena (*Pallas Athena*).', 'Παλλάς', 'Pallas', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000265', 'Cacus', 'masculine', 'Latin name possibly meaning "bad" or "evil". From Latin *cacus* related to Greek *kakos* (*κακός*) "bad". In Roman mythology and Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Cacus is a fire-breathing giant, part-human monster begotten by Vulcan, slain by Hercules on the site of future Rome.', 'Cacus', 'Cacus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000266', 'Potitius', 'masculine', 'Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from *potis* "able, powerful". In Roman tradition and Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Potitius is founder of priestly rites at Pallanteum honoring Hercules'' slaying of Cacus. Associated with the "Greatest Altar" (*Ara Maxima*) and the Pinarian house guarding Hercules worship.', 'Potitius', 'Potitius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000267', 'Salus', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "health", "safety", "welfare". From Latin *salus*. Roman goddess of health, prosperity, and public welfare. Also used as a greeting meaning "greetings" or "good health".', 'Salus', 'Salus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000268', 'Salius', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning "leaping" or "dancing". From Latin *salire* "to leap, to dance". The Salii were the dancing priests of Mars in ancient Rome who performed ritual war dances wearing archaic armor.', 'Salius', 'Salius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000269', 'Oechalia', 'feminine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology. Ancient Greek city conquered and razed by Heracles. Multiple cities in Greece claimed this name in tradition. Scene of Heracles'' vengeance against King Eurytus.', 'Οἰχαλία', 'Oechalia', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000270', 'Eurystheus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "wide strength" or "broad might". From Greek *eurys* (*εὐρύς*) "wide, broad" + *sthenos* (*σθένος*) "strength, might". In Greek mythology, Eurystheus is the king of Tiryns who assigned Heracles his Twelve Labors.', 'Εὐρυσθεύς', 'Eurystheus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000271', 'Hylaeus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "of the forest" or "woodland dweller". From Greek *hyle* (*ὕλη*) "forest, wood". In Greek mythology, Hylaeus is a centaur born of clouds, killed by Heracles during the battle with the centaurs.', 'Ὑλαῖος', 'Hylaeus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000272', 'Pholus', 'masculine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "den" or "cave-dweller". In Greek mythology, Pholus is a wise and hospitable centaur born of clouds, friend to Heracles, accidentally killed during the battle with other centaurs.', 'Φόλος', 'Pholus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000273', 'Thybris', 'masculine', 'Greek name for the Tiber River. From Greek *Thybris* (*Θύβρις*), variant of *Thymbris*. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Thybris is the river god of the Tiber who appears to Aeneas in a dream, guiding him upriver to Pallanteum.', 'Θύβρις', 'Thybris', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000274', 'Albula', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "whitish" or "pale water". From Latin *albus* "white". Ancient name of the Tiber River before King Tiberinus drowned in it and the river was renamed in his memory.', 'Albula', 'Albula', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000275', 'Carmentis', 'feminine', 'Latin name possibly from *carmen* "song, prophecy, incantation". Roman nymph and goddess of prophecy and childbirth, described as "seer who told the truth". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Carmentis is the mother of Evander and namesake of the Carmental Gate (*Porta Carmentalis*) in Rome.', 'Carmentis', 'Carmentis', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000276', 'Asylum', 'neuter', 'Greek/Latin name meaning "sanctuary" or "refuge". From Greek *asylos* (*ἄσυλος*) "inviolable, without right of seizure". In Roman tradition, the Asylum was a sacred grove on the Capitoline Hill where Romulus offered refuge to fugitives when he was a refugee, helping populate early Rome.', 'Asylum', 'Asylum', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000277', 'Lupercal', 'neuter', 'Latin name meaning "wolf grotto". From Latin *lupus* "wolf" + *-cal* locative suffix. Sacred grotto under the Asylum at the foot of the Palatine Hill, legendary site where the she-wolf nursed Romulus and Remus. Named after Pan of Mount Lycaeus (Pan Lycaeus, wolf-Pan).', 'Lupercal', 'Lupercal', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000278', 'Lycaeus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "wolfish" or "of the wolf". From Greek *lykos* (*λύκος*) "wolf" + adjectival suffix. Mount Lycaeus in Arcadia, sacred to Zeus Lycaeus and Pan, ancient site of wolf cults and secret rites.', 'Λύκαιος', 'Lycaeus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000279', 'Tarpeia', 'feminine', 'Latin name of Sabine origin, possibly from *tarpeia* "rocky crag". In Roman legend, Tarpeia was a Vestal Virgin who betrayed Rome to the Sabines during the Sabine Wars. The Tarpeian Rock (*Saxum Tarpeium*), from which traitors and murderers were thrown to their deaths, is named after her.', 'Tarpeia', 'Tarpeia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000280', 'Carinae', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "keels" or "ship hulls". From Latin *carina* "keel". Ancient district of Rome on the Oppian Hill, named for its ridge-like shape resembling the keel of an overturned ship.', 'Carinae', 'Carinae', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000281', 'Aurora', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "dawn" or "sunrise". From Latin *aurora* "dawn", cognate with Greek *Eos* (*Ἠώς*). Roman goddess of the dawn, bringer of morning light, equivalent to Greek Eos.', 'Aurora', 'Aurora', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000282', 'Tithonus', 'masculine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly pre-Greek. In Greek mythology, Tithonus is the Trojan prince and lover of Eos (Aurora), granted immortality but not eternal youth, eventually transformed into a cicada.', 'Τιθωνός', 'Tithonus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000283', 'Nereus', 'masculine', 'Greek name possibly meaning "wet" or "flowing water". From Greek *neros* (*νηρός*) "wet, fresh, flowing". In Greek mythology, Nereus is the "Old Man of the Sea," a sea god, father of the fifty Nereids, known for his truthfulness, wisdom, and shape-shifting abilities.', 'Νηρεύς', 'Nereus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000284', 'Lipare', 'feminine', 'Greek/Latin name meaning "shining" or "oily-smooth". From Greek *liparos* (*λιπαρός*) "oily, shining, sleek". Ancient name for the Aeolian Islands (Lipari Islands) north of Sicily, sacred to Hephaestus/Vulcan, site of his forge.', 'Λιπάρη', 'Lipare', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000285', 'Etna', 'feminine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly from pre-Greek or Phoenician substrate. Mount Etna (*Aetna*) in Sicily, Europe''s highest active volcano. In mythology, the forge of Hephaestus/Vulcan and prison of the monster Typhon beneath the mountain.', 'Αἴτνη', 'Etna', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000286', 'Vulcani', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning "of Vulcan" or "Vulcan''s (places)". Plural or genitive form referring to the volcanic regions, islands, and forges sacred to Vulcan, god of fire, metalworking, and volcanoes.', 'Vulcani', 'Vulcani', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000287', 'Tarchon', 'masculine', 'Etruscan name of uncertain etymology. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Tarchon is the legendary founder of Tarquinia and leader of the Etruscan forces allied with Aeneas against Turnus and the Latins.', 'Tarchon', 'Tarchon', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000288', 'Propertius', 'masculine', 'Latin name derived from *proprius* "one''s own, proper, peculiar". Famous bearer: Sextus Propertius (c. 50-15 BCE), Roman elegiac poet of the Augustan age, known for his passionate love poems to Cynthia.', 'Propertius', 'Propertius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000289', 'Anchemolus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Greek *agkhi* (*ἀγχι*) "near" + *molos* (*μόλος*) "toil, struggle, battle". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, Anchemolus is a Trojan warrior who fights alongside Aeneas.', 'Anchemolus', 'Anchemolus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000290', 'Manius', 'masculine', 'Latin praenomen, abbreviated *M''* or *M.* Derived from *mane* "morning, early" or *Manes* (spirits of the dead). One of the rarer Roman praenomina, used primarily by certain families.', 'Manius', 'Manius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000291', 'Curius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) of uncertain etymology. Famous bearer: Manius Curius Dentatus, Roman consul and general (c. 290-270 BCE) who defeated Pyrrhus of Epirus, symbol of old Roman virtue and simplicity.', 'Curius', 'Curius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000292', 'Dentatus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning "toothed" or "having prominent teeth". From Latin *dentatus*, past participle of *dentare* "to furnish with teeth", from *dens*, genitive *dentis* "tooth". Famous bearer: Manius Curius Dentatus, military hero and symbol of Roman virtue.', 'Dentatus', 'Dentatus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000293', 'Telesinus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name meaning "far-reaching" or "accomplished one". From Greek *tele* (*τῆλε*) "far, at a distance" + suffix. Historical bearer: Pontius Telesinus, Samnite general who fought against Rome in the Social War (91-88 BCE).', 'Telesinus', 'Telesinus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000294', 'Numina', 'neuter', 'Latin name meaning "divine powers" or "divine wills". Plural of *numen* "divine power, deity, divine will, nod of the head". In Roman religion, numina are the divine powers, presences, or spirits inhabiting all things in nature.', 'Numina', 'Numina', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000295', 'Numinus', 'masculine', 'Latin name derived from *numen* "divine power, deity, divinity". Means "of the divine power" or "divine, numinous". Related to the numinous quality of sacred presence and divine manifestation.', 'Numinus', 'Numinus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000296', 'Pytheas', 'masculine', 'Greek name derived from *Pythios* (*Πύθιος*), epithet of Apollo at Delphi. From *Python* (*Πύθων*), the serpent slain by Apollo. Famous bearer: Pytheas of Massalia (c. 350-285 BCE), Greek explorer and geographer who traveled to Britain and possibly the Arctic Circle.', 'Πυθέας', 'Pytheas', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000297', 'Ateas', 'masculine', 'Scythian name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "horseman" or related to Iranian roots for strength. Historical bearer: Ateas (c. 429-339 BCE), king of the Pontic Scythians, killed in battle against Philip II of Macedon at age 90.', 'Ἀτέας', 'Ateas', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000298', 'Meda', 'feminine', 'Thracian/Greek name possibly meaning "cunning" or "counsels". From Greek *medea* (*μήδεα*) "plans, counsels, cunning". Historical bearer: Meda of Odessos, Thracian princess of the Getae, one of the wives of Philip II of Macedon and mother of Cynane.', 'Μήδα', 'Meda', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000299', 'Cothelas', 'masculine', 'Thracian name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Thracian royal lineage or meaning "leader". Historical bearer: Cothelas, king of the Getae (Thracian tribe) and father of Meda, allied with Philip II of Macedon through marriage.', 'Κοθήλας', 'Cothelas', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000300', 'Spitamenes', 'masculine', 'Sogdian/Persian name possibly meaning "having white horses" or "white strength". From Old Persian *spita-* "white, bright" + *aspa* "horse" or *-mana* "minded". Historical bearer: Spitamenes (d. 328 BCE), Sogdian warlord who led a major uprising against Alexander the Great in Bactria and Sogdiana.', 'Σπιταμένης', 'Spitamenes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000301', 'Bucephalus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "ox-head". From Greek *bous* (*βοῦς*) "ox, bull" + *kephale* (*κεφαλή*) "head". The legendary warhorse of Alexander the Great (c. 355-326 BCE), so named for a white mark on his forehead shaped like an ox''s head, or for his broad forehead.', 'Βουκέφαλος', 'Bucephalus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000302', 'Roxana', 'feminine', 'Sogdian/Persian name meaning "bright" or "dawn, little star". From Old Iranian *raoxšna-* "bright, shining, luminous". Historical bearer: Roxana (c. 340-310 BCE), Sogdian/Bactrian princess, first wife of Alexander the Great, mother of Alexander IV of Macedon.', 'Ῥωξάνη', 'Roxana', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000303', 'Stateira', 'feminine', 'Persian name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Old Persian *ṛtāvari-* "possessing truth" or "having cosmic order". Historical bearer: Stateira II, daughter of Darius III of Persia, second (or third) wife of Alexander the Great, married at Susa in 324 BCE.', 'Στάτειρα', 'Stateira', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000304', 'Cynane', 'feminine', 'Macedonian/Illyrian name possibly from Greek *kyon* (*κύων*), genitive *kynos* (*κυνός*) "dog" + suffix, or Illyrian roots. Historical bearer: Cynane (c. 357-323 BCE), daughter of Philip II of Macedon and the Illyrian princess Audata, half-sister of Alexander the Great, renowned warrior woman.', 'Κυνάνη', 'Cynane', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000305', 'Audata', 'feminine', 'Illyrian name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Illyrian royal lineage or meaning "wealth, prosperity". Historical bearer: Audata (also called Eurydice after marriage), Illyrian princess, first wife of Philip II of Macedon, mother of the warrior Cynane.', 'Αὐδάτα', 'Audata', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000306', 'Wenia', 'feminine', 'Celtic name meaning "blessed river" or "forest stream". From Proto-Celtic *wenjā* "blessed, holy, favored" or possibly *widus* "forest" + river element. Ancient Celtic name for a sacred river in Gaul.', 'Wenia', 'Wenia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000307', 'Vedunia', 'feminine', 'Celtic name meaning "forest river" or "woodland stream". From Proto-Celtic *widus* "forest, wood" + *dunom* "fort, stronghold" or river element. Variant form of Wenia, ancient Celtic river name in Gaul.', 'Vedunia', 'Vedunia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000308', 'Aristarchus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "best ruler" or "excellent leader". From Greek *aristos* (*ἄριστος*) "best, excellent" + *archos* (*ἀρχός*) "ruler, leader". Famous bearers: Aristarchus of Samos (c. 310-230 BCE), astronomer who proposed heliocentric model; Aristarchus of Samothrace (c. 220-143 BCE), grammarian and critic.', 'Ἀρίσταρχος', 'Aristarchus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000309', 'Hypatia', 'feminine', 'Greek name meaning "highest" or "supreme". From Greek *hypatos* (*ὕπατος*) "highest, uppermost, supreme". Famous bearer: Hypatia of Alexandria (c. 350-415 CE), mathematician, astronomer, and philosopher, head of the Neoplatonic school in Alexandria.', 'Ὑπατία', 'Hypatia', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000310', 'Ammonius', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "of Ammon" or "belonging to Ammon". From the Egyptian god Ammon (Amun). Famous bearers: Ammonius Saccas (c. 175-242 CE), founder of Neoplatonism and teacher of Plotinus; Ammonius Hermiae (5th-6th century CE), Neoplatonic philosopher.', 'Ἀμμώνιος', 'Ammonius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000311', 'Porphyry', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "purple" or "clad in purple". From Greek *porphyra* (*πορφύρα*) "purple dye, purple garment". Famous bearer: Porphyry of Tyre (c. 234-305 CE), Neoplatonic philosopher, student of Plotinus, editor of the *Enneads*.', 'Πορφύριος', 'Porphyry', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000312', 'Numenius', 'masculine', 'Greek name possibly meaning "of the new moon" or from *noumenia* "new moon festival". From Greek *noumenia* (*νουμηνία*). Famous bearer: Numenius of Apamea (2nd century CE), Platonist philosopher who synthesized Greek and Eastern thought, influential on Neoplatonism.', 'Νουμήνιος', 'Numenius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000313', 'Empedocles', 'masculine', 'Greek name possibly meaning "native glory" or "care of glory". From Greek *en* (*ἐν*) "in" + *mede-* "care" + *kleos* (*κλέος*) "glory, fame". Famous bearer: Empedocles of Akragas (c. 494-434 BCE), pre-Socratic philosopher who proposed four classical elements (earth, air, fire, water).', 'Ἐμπεδοκλῆς', 'Empedocles', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000314', 'Heraclitus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "glory of Hera". From Greek *Hera* (*Ἥρα*), goddess + *kleos* (*κλέος*) "glory, fame". Famous bearer: Heraclitus of Ephesus (c. 535-475 BCE), pre-Socratic philosopher known for doctrine of change ("everything flows") and concept of Logos.', 'Ἡράκλειτος', 'Heraclitus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000315', 'Castricius', 'masculine', 'Latin name derived from *castrum* "fort, castle, military camp". Possibly meaning "of the camp" or "military". Historical bearer: Castricius Firmus, Roman senator and friend of Plotinus, member of his philosophical circle in Rome.', 'Castricius', 'Castricius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000316', 'Eustochius', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "good aim" or "well-targeted". From Greek *eu* (*εὖ*) "good, well" + *stochos* (*στόχος*) "aim, target, goal". Historical bearer: Eustochius of Alexandria (3rd century CE), physician and student of Plotinus, edited and published the *Enneads*.', 'Εὐστόχιος', 'Eustochius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000317', 'Zethos', 'masculine', 'Greek name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "searcher" or from *zetein* (*ζητεῖν*) "to seek, search for". In Greek mythology, Zethos is the twin brother of Amphion, son of Zeus and Antiope, co-founder of Thebes.', 'Ζῆθος', 'Zethos', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000318', 'Ariston', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "the best" or "most excellent". From Greek *aristos* (*ἄριστος*) "best, excellent". Multiple historical bearers including philosophers and aristocrats. Used as both a proper name and honorific.', 'Ἀρίστων', 'Ariston', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000319', 'Iamblichus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Aramaic name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Semitic roots meaning "king" or Syrian origins. Famous bearer: Iamblichus of Chalcis (c. 245-325 CE), Neoplatonic philosopher, developed theurgy (ritual magic) as spiritual practice, influenced later mysticism.', 'Ἰάμβλιχος', 'Iamblichus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000320', 'Phormio', 'masculine', 'Greek name possibly meaning "basket-carrier" or "mat-maker". From Greek *phormos* (*φορμός*) "woven mat, basket". Famous bearer: Phormio (5th century BCE), Athenian general known for naval victories during the Peloponnesian War.', 'Φορμίων', 'Phormio', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000321', 'Prusias', 'masculine', 'Greek/Bithynian name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Thracian or Anatolian roots. Historical bearers: Prusias I and II, kings of Bithynia (3rd-2nd century BCE). The city of Prusa (modern Bursa, Turkey) was named after Prusias I.', 'Προυσίας', 'Prusias', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000322', 'Eumenes', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "well-disposed" or "kindly minded". From Greek *eu* (*εὖ*) "good, well" + *menos* (*μένος*) "spirit, mind, intent". Famous bearer: Eumenes of Cardia (c. 362-316 BCE), Greek general and one of the Diadochi (successors) of Alexander the Great.', 'Εὐμενής', 'Eumenes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000323', 'Livius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) possibly from *lividus* "bluish, envious" or Etruscan origin. Famous bearers: Titus Livius (Livy, 59 BCE-17 CE), Roman historian who wrote *Ab Urbe Condita* (History of Rome); Livius Andronicus, earliest Roman poet.', 'Livius', 'Livius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000324', 'Drusus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen of uncertain etymology, possibly from Gallic *drausus* "strong, vigorous". Famous bearers: Multiple members of the Claudian gens, including Nero Claudius Drusus (38-9 BCE), general and brother of Emperor Tiberius.', 'Drusus', 'Drusus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000325', 'Sulla', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen of uncertain etymology, possibly from *sulla* "a red spot" or related to physical markings. Famous bearer: Lucius Cornelius Sulla Felix (138-78 BCE), Roman general and dictator who reformed the Roman constitution.', 'Sulla', 'Sulla', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000326', 'Metellus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen possibly from *metella* "small pyramid" or *mercenarius* "hired worker". Multiple famous bearers from the Caecilii Metelli family, one of the most powerful plebeian families in the late Roman Republic.', 'Metellus', 'Metellus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000327', 'Caecilius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) possibly from *caecus* "blind" or Etruscan origin. The gens Caecilia was one of the most prominent plebeian families in Rome. Famous bearers include Caecilius Statius (c. 220-166 BCE), comic playwright; and the Caecilii Metelli, a powerful branch of the family that produced numerous consuls and generals.', 'Caecilius', 'Caecilius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000328', 'Caecilus', 'masculine', 'Latin variant spelling of Caecilius. Archaic or alternative form of the nomen Caecilius, from *caecus* "blind". Used interchangeably with Caecilius in various inscriptions and texts. Associated with the gens Caecilia.', 'Caecilus', 'Caecilus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Carthaginian (Punic) Names
('NA000329', 'Hannibal', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "grace of Baal" or "Baal is gracious". From Phoenician *ḥnn* (𐤇𐤍𐤍) "grace, favor" + *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord, master". Famous bearer: Hannibal Barca (247-183 BCE), Carthaginian general who crossed the Alps with war elephants and nearly defeated Rome during the Second Punic War.', '𐤇𐤍𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Hannibal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000330', 'Hamilcar', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "brother of Melqart" or "servant of Melqart". From Phoenician *ḥml* (𐤇𐤌𐤋) "brother, servant" + *Melqart* (𐤌𐤋𐤒𐤓𐤕) (chief god of Tyre). Famous bearer: Hamilcar Barca (c. 275-228 BCE), Carthaginian general, father of Hannibal, who conquered much of Hispania.', '𐤇𐤌𐤋𐤒𐤓𐤕', 'Hamilcar', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000331', 'Hasdrubal', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "Baal helps" or "help of Baal". From Phoenician *ʿzr* (𐤏𐤆𐤓) "help, aid" + *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord". Multiple famous bearers including Hasdrubal Barca (c. 245-207 BCE), brother of Hannibal who commanded Carthaginian forces in Hispania.', '𐤏𐤆𐤓𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Hasdrubal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000332', 'Himilco', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "brother of the king" or "Melqart is my brother". From Phoenician *ḥml* (𐤇𐤌𐤋) "brother" + *mlk* (𐤌𐤋𐤊) "king". Multiple historical bearers including Himilco the Navigator (5th century BCE), Carthaginian explorer who sailed to northwestern Europe.', '𐤇𐤌𐤋𐤊', 'Himilco', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000333', 'Tanit', 'feminine', 'Punic/Phoenician name of uncertain etymology, possibly from Berber or Libyan origins. Tanit (also Tanith, Tinnit) was the chief goddess of Carthage, associated with fertility, the moon, and war. Consort of Baal Hammon. Her symbol was the "Sign of Tanit" - a triangle with a horizontal line and circle above.', '𐤕𐤍𐤕', 'Tanit', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000334', 'Baal', 'masculine', 'Phoenician/Canaanite name meaning "lord", "master", "owner". From Northwest Semitic *baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋). Title and name of various deities throughout the ancient Near East. In Carthage, Baal Hammon was the supreme god, often associated with Saturn.', '𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Baal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000335', 'Hanno', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "gracious" or "merciful". From Phoenician *ḥnn* (𐤇𐤍𐤍) "to be gracious, to show favor". A shortened form related to Hannibal. Historical bearers include various Carthaginian officials and military commanders.', '𐤇𐤍', 'Hano', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000336', 'Mago', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "gift" or related to *mgn* (𐤌𐤂𐤍) "gift, offering". Multiple famous bearers including Mago Barca, youngest brother of Hannibal; and Mago the Agriculturist (3rd century BCE), whose agricultural treatise was highly respected by Romans.', '𐤌𐤂𐤍', 'Mago', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000337', 'Maharbal', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "Baal''s gift" or "blessed by Baal". From Phoenician *mhr* (𐤌𐤇𐤓) "gift, reward" + *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord". Famous bearer: Maharbal (fl. 216 BCE), Carthaginian cavalry commander under Hannibal, who famously urged Hannibal to march on Rome immediately after Cannae.', '𐤌𐤇𐤓𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Maharbal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000338', 'Gisgo', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name of uncertain etymology, possibly meaning "stranger" or "sojourner". Multiple historical bearers including Gisco (various spellings), Carthaginian general captured after the Battle of Zama, and other military commanders during the Punic Wars.', '𐤂𐤔𐤒', 'Gisgo', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000339', 'Carthalo', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name possibly meaning "of Carthage" or derived from *Qart-ḥadašt* (𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤇𐤃𐤔𐤕) "New City" (Carthage itself). Multiple historical bearers including Carthalo, Carthaginian cavalry commander under Hannibal during the Second Punic War.', '𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤇𐤃𐤔𐤕', 'Carthalo', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000340', 'Bomilcar', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "in the protection of Melqart" or "servant of Melqart". From Phoenician *b-* "in, with" + *ʿbd* (𐤏𐤁𐤃) "servant" + *Melqart* (𐤌𐤋𐤒𐤓𐤕) (Tyrian god). Multiple historical bearers including Bomilcar, Carthaginian admiral and politician who attempted a coup in the 4th century BCE.', '𐤁𐤏𐤌𐤋𐤒𐤓𐤕', 'Bomilcar', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000341', 'Phameas', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name of uncertain etymology, possibly related to Egyptian or Greek influences on Punic culture. Historical bearer: Phameas (Phanes), Carthaginian cavalry commander who defected to Rome during the Third Punic War (149-146 BCE).', '𐤐𐤇𐤌𐤏𐤔', 'Phameas', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000342', 'Diogenes', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "born of Zeus". From Greek *Dios* (*Διός*), genitive of *Zeus* (*Ζεύς*) + *genes* (*γενής*) "born". Historical bearer in Carthaginian context: Diogenes, Greek military engineer who served Carthage during the Third Punic War, expert in siege warfare.', 'Διογένης', 'Diogenes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000343', 'Byrsa', 'feminine', 'Punic/Greek name meaning "citadel" or "hide". From Greek *byrsa* (*βύρσα*) "oxhide", referring to the Carthaginian foundation legend where Queen Dido bought as much land as could be enclosed by an oxhide, which she cut into thin strips. Byrsa was the fortified hill and citadel of Carthage.', '𐤁𐤓𐤎', 'Byrsa', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000344', 'Melqart', 'masculine', 'Phoenician name meaning "king of the city". From Phoenician *mlk* (𐤌𐤋𐤊) "king" + *qrt* (𐤒𐤓𐤕) "city". Melqart was the chief god of Tyre, protector of the Phoenician city and its colonies including Carthage. Associated with kingship, navigation, and often identified with Heracles by the Greeks. His temple at Tyre was one of the most famous in antiquity.', '𐤌𐤋𐤒𐤓𐤕', 'Melqart', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000345', 'Azarbaal', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "Baal helps" or "helped by Baal". From Phoenician *ʿzr* (𐤏𐤆𐤓) "help, aid" + *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord". Alternative form or variant of Hasdrubal. Historical bearers include Carthaginian nobles and officials during the Punic period.', '𐤏𐤆𐤓𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Azarbaal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000346', 'Baalhanno', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "Baal is gracious" or "gift of Baal''s grace". From Phoenician *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord" + *ḥnn* (𐤇𐤍𐤍) "grace, favor". Compound theophoric name combining the chief deity with the concept of divine grace. Multiple Carthaginian officials and military leaders bore this name.', '𐤁𐤏𐤋𐤇𐤍', 'Baalhanno', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000347', 'Eshmun', 'masculine', 'Phoenician name possibly meaning "the eighth" or from Semitic root *šmn* (𐤔𐤌𐤍) "oil, fat" (related to healing). Eshmun was the Phoenician god of healing and rejuvenation, patron deity of Sidon. In Carthage, he was highly venerated with major temples. Often identified with Greek Asclepius (god of medicine).', '𐤀𐤔𐤌𐤍', 'Eshmun', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000348', 'Eshmunazar', 'masculine', 'Phoenician name meaning "Eshmun helps" or "helped by Eshmun". From *Eshmun* (𐤀𐤔𐤌𐤍) (healing god) + *ʿzr* (𐤏𐤆𐤓) "help, aid". Famous bearer: Eshmunazar II (6th-5th century BCE), king of Sidon whose magnificent sarcophagus with Phoenician inscription is now in the Louvre Museum.', '𐤀𐤔𐤌𐤍𐤏𐤆𐤓', 'Eshmunazar', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000349', 'Adherbal', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name meaning "servant of Baal" or "Baal is my help". From Phoenician *ʿdr* (𐤏𐤃𐤓) "help, support" or *ʿbd* (𐤏𐤁𐤃) "servant" + *Baʿal* (𐤁𐤏𐤋) "lord". Multiple historical bearers including Adherbal, last king of Numidia who was defeated by his brother Jugurtha, leading to Roman intervention (112 BCE).', '𐤏𐤃𐤓𐤁𐤏𐤋', 'Adherbal', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000350', 'Bostar', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name possibly meaning "in the hand of Astarte" or "protected by Astarte". From Phoenician *b-* "in, with" + *yad* (𐤉𐤃) "hand" or possession marker + *ʿAštart* (𐤏𐤔𐤕𐤓𐤕) (goddess). Multiple Carthaginian military commanders and officials bore this name, including Bostar who served under Hannibal during the Second Punic War.', '𐤁𐤏𐤔𐤕𐤓', 'Bostar', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000351', 'Xanthippus', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "yellow horse" or "tawny horse". From Greek *xanthos* (*ξανθός*) "yellow, blonde, tawny" + *hippos* (*ἵππος*) "horse". Famous bearer: Xanthippus of Sparta (fl. 255 BCE), Spartan mercenary general who reorganized the Carthaginian army and defeated the Roman general Marcus Atilius Regulus at the Battle of Tunis during the First Punic War.', 'Ξάνθιππος', 'Xanthippus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000352', 'Lutatius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) of uncertain etymology, possibly from Oscan or related to *lutum* "mud, clay". Associated with the gens Lutatia. Famous bearer: Gaius Lutatius Catulus (fl. 242 BCE), Roman consul and admiral who defeated the Carthaginian fleet at the Battle of the Aegates Islands, ending the First Punic War.', 'Lutatius', 'Lutatius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000353', 'Carthalo', 'masculine', 'Punic/Phoenician name possibly meaning "of Carthage" or derived from *Qart-ḥadašt* (𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤇𐤃𐤔𐤕) "New City" (Carthage itself). Historical bearer: Carthalo, Carthaginian officer sent to Rome in 216 BCE after the Battle of Cannae to negotiate terms, but was denied entry to the city by the Senate.', '𐤒𐤓𐤕𐤋', 'Carthalo', 'RR00010', 'SC00004', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000354', 'Vipsania', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Vipsanian family". From the gens Vipsania. Famous bearer: Vipsania Agrippina (36 BCE-20 CE), daughter of Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, first wife of the future emperor Tiberius. Her forced divorce from Tiberius to marry Julia (daughter of Augustus) was a personal tragedy that affected Tiberius deeply.', 'Vipsania', 'Vipsania', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000355', 'Pomponia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Pomponian family". From the gens Pomponia. Famous bearer: Pomponia Graecina (1st century CE), Roman noblewoman and wife of Aulus Plautius (conqueror of Britain), noted for her long mourning dress and suspected of following foreign superstitions, possibly Christianity. Also Pomponia, beloved wife of Cicero''s brother Quintus and sister of his friend Atticus.', 'Pomponia', 'Pomponia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000356', 'Haterius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) of uncertain etymology, possibly from Oscan or Sabine origins. Associated with the gens Hateria. Famous bearer: Quintus Haterius (c. 65 BCE-26 CE), Roman senator and orator known for his rapid and impetuous speaking style. Tacitus describes him as having eloquence that died with him due to its unpolished, breathless delivery.', 'Haterius', 'Haterius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000357', 'Seneca', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning "old man" or "aged". From Latin *senex* "old man, elder". Famous bearers: Seneca the Elder (c. 54 BCE-39 CE), Roman rhetorician and writer; and his son Seneca the Younger (c. 4 BCE-65 CE), Stoic philosopher, statesman, dramatist, and advisor to Emperor Nero, forced to commit suicide after being implicated in the Pisonian conspiracy.', 'Seneca', 'Seneca', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000358', 'Piso', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning "pestle" or "pounder". From Latin *piso*, *pisare* "to pound, to crush". Branch of the gens Calpurnia. Famous bearers: Lucius Calpurnius Piso Caesoninus, father-in-law of Julius Caesar and patron of the philosopher Philodemus; Gnaeus Calpurnius Piso, accused of poisoning Germanicus; Gaius Calpurnius Piso, leader of the Pisonian conspiracy against Nero (65 CE).', 'Piso', 'Piso', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000359', 'Ofonius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) of uncertain etymology, possibly from Oscan origins. Associated with the gens Ofonia. Famous bearer: Ofonius Tigellinus (c. 10-69 CE), Praetorian prefect under Emperor Nero, notorious for his cruelty, corruption, and role in the persecution of Christians after the Great Fire of Rome (64 CE).', 'Ofonius', 'Ofonius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000360', 'Tigelinus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen of uncertain etymology, possibly diminutive or related to regional origins. Famous bearer: Ofonius Tigellinus (c. 10-69 CE), Praetorian prefect and close advisor to Emperor Nero. Known for his cruelty, debauchery, and role in the Great Fire of Rome. He encouraged Nero''s worst excesses and orchestrated persecutions of Christians and political enemies. Forced to commit suicide under Otho.', 'Tigelinus', 'Tigelinus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000361', 'Vitellius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) possibly derived from *vitulus* "calf" or from the Sabine town of Vitelia. Associated with the gens Vitellia. Famous bearer: Aulus Vitellius (15-69 CE), Roman emperor during the Year of the Four Emperors, known for his gluttony and brief tumultuous reign of eight months before being murdered by supporters of Vespasian.', 'Vitellius', 'Vitellius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000362', 'Otho', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen of uncertain etymology, possibly from Germanic or Etruscan origins. Famous bearer: Marcus Salvius Otho (32-69 CE), Roman emperor during the Year of the Four Emperors. Former friend of Nero and husband of Poppaea Sabina before Nero took her as his wife. Ruled for three months after overthrowing Galba, then committed suicide after losing the Battle of Bedriacum to Vitellius.', 'Otho', 'Otho', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000363', 'Salvius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) derived from *salvus* "safe, healthy, sound". Associated with the gens Salvia. Famous bearer: Marcus Salvius Otho (Emperor Otho), who adopted the name Salvius from his maternal grandfather. The name reflects the wish for safety and well-being.', 'Salvius', 'Salvius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000364', 'Poppaea', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Poppaean family". From the gens Poppaea. Famous bearer: Poppaea Sabina (30-65 CE), second wife of Emperor Nero, renowned for her beauty. First married to Rufrius Crispinus, then to Otho (who was exiled when Nero desired her), and finally to Nero himself. Died from Nero kicking her while pregnant, according to ancient sources.', 'Poppaea', 'Poppaea', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000365', 'Ollia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Ollian family". From the gens Ollia, variant spelling of Allia. Historical bearer: Allia Potestas (also spelled Ollia), mother of Emperor Otho. The name may be related to the river Allia or have Etruscan origins.', 'Ollia', 'Ollia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000366', 'Ollius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) meaning "of the Ollian family". From the gens Ollia, variant spelling of Allius. May be related to the river Allia or have Etruscan origins. Historical bearer: Titus Ollius, father of Poppaea Sabina and member of the equestrian order who was destroyed by the friendship of Sejanus.', 'Ollius', 'Ollius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Additional Roman Imperial Names and Cognomina
('NA000367', 'Nero', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning "strong, vigorous, brave" or possibly from Sabine origins. Famous bearer: Nero Claudius Caesar Augustus Germanicus (37-68 CE), fifth Roman emperor, adopted son of Claudius. Also used by the Claudian gens, including Nero Claudius Drusus (brother of Tiberius). The name became synonymous with tyranny after the emperor Nero''s reign.', 'Nero', 'Nero', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000368', 'Niger', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning *niger* "black, dark", typically referring to dark hair or complexion. Famous bearers include Pescennius Niger (140-194 CE), Roman general who claimed the imperial throne after the death of Pertinax, defeated by Septimius Severus. Common cognomen in various Roman families.', 'Niger', 'Niger', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000369', 'Parthicus', 'masculine', 'Latin agnomen (victory title) meaning "conqueror of Parthia" or "victor over the Parthians". From *Parthi* (Parthians) + suffix *-icus*. Honorary title awarded to Roman emperors and generals for victories over the Parthian Empire. Famous bearers: Trajan (Parthicus, 116 CE), Septimius Severus (Parthicus Maximus), Caracalla (Parthicus Maximus). Not a birth name but an earned honor.', 'Parthicus', 'Parthicus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000370', 'Germanicus', 'masculine', 'Latin agnomen (victory title) meaning "conqueror of Germania" or "victor over the Germans". From *Germani* (Germanic peoples) + suffix *-icus*. Originally awarded to Nero Claudius Drusus for his victories in Germania (9 BCE), the title became hereditary in his branch of the Claudian family. Most famous bearer: Germanicus Julius Caesar (15 BCE-19 CE), adopted son of Tiberius, popular general and father of Caligula. Also used as an imperial victory title.', 'Germanicus', 'Germanicus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000371', 'Britannicus', 'masculine', 'Latin agnomen (victory title) meaning "conqueror of Britain" or "victor over the Britons". From *Britanni* (Britons) + suffix *-icus*. Originally awarded to Emperor Claudius for the conquest of Britain (43 CE). Famous bearer: Tiberius Claudius Caesar Britannicus (41-55 CE), son of Emperor Claudius and Messalina, intended heir who was passed over in favor of Nero and allegedly poisoned by him. The name honored his father''s British conquest.', 'Britannicus', 'Britannicus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000372', 'Creticus', 'masculine', 'Latin agnomen (victory title) meaning "conqueror of Crete" or "victor over the Cretans". From *Creta* (Crete) + suffix *-icus*. Famous bearer: Quintus Caecilius Metellus Creticus (c. 130-55 BCE), Roman general and statesman who conquered Crete (69-67 BCE) and was awarded this honorary title. Also Publius Servilius Vatia Isauricus received "Creticus" for campaigns against Cretan pirates.', 'Creticus', 'Creticus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000373', 'Julia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Julian family". From the gens Iulia, one of Rome''s most ancient patrician families claiming descent from Iulus (Ascanius), son of Aeneas and grandson of Venus. Numerous famous bearers including: Julia (daughter of Julius Caesar and wife of Pompey), Julia (daughter of Augustus), Julia Agrippina (mother of Nero), Julia Domna (wife of Septimius Severus). The name epitomizes Roman aristocratic lineage.', 'Julia', 'Julia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000374', 'Gabinius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) possibly derived from the city Gabii or from Etruscan origins. Associated with the gens Gabinia. Famous bearer: Aulus Gabinius (c. 110-48 BCE), Roman statesman and general, consul in 58 BCE, supported Pompey and restored Ptolemy XII to the Egyptian throne. The Lex Gabinia (67 BCE) granted Pompey extraordinary command against Mediterranean pirates.', 'Gabinius', 'Gabinius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000375', 'Antonia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Antonian family". From the gens Antonia, possibly derived from Greek *anthos* "flower" or Etruscan origins. Famous bearers include: Antonia Minor (36 BCE-37 CE), daughter of Mark Antony and Octavia, mother of Emperor Claudius and Germanicus, grandmother of Caligula; Antonia Major (sister of Antonia Minor). The name represents one of Rome''s most prominent plebeian families.', 'Antonia', 'Antonia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000376', 'Manilius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) possibly derived from *manus* "hand" or from Etruscan origins. Associated with the gens Manilia. Famous bearers include: Marcus Manilius (1st century CE), Roman poet and astrologer, author of *Astronomica*; Manius Manilius (consul 149 BCE), jurist and one of the founders of Roman civil law; Gaius Manilius (tribune 66 BCE), proposed the Lex Manilia granting Pompey command in the Third Mithridatic War.', 'Manilius', 'Manilius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000377', 'Vesuvius', 'masculine', 'Latin name derived from Mount Vesuvius (*Vesuvius mons*), the volcano near Naples. Etymology possibly from Oscan or pre-Indo-European substrate, possibly meaning "the unquenchable" or related to *Vesuvius* (a local deity). Famous for the catastrophic eruption in 79 CE that destroyed Pompeii and Herculaneum. Used occasionally as a cognomen or personal name, symbolizing both destructive power and the fertile lands around the mountain.', 'Vesuvius', 'Vesuvius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000378', 'Vitruvius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen (family name) of uncertain etymology, possibly from Etruscan origins or related to *vetus* "old". Associated with the gens Vitruvia. Most famous bearer: Marcus Vitruvius Pollio (c. 80-15 BCE), Roman architect, engineer, and author of *De architectura* (*On Architecture*), the only surviving ancient treatise on architecture, which profoundly influenced Renaissance architecture.', 'Vitruvius', 'Vitruvius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000379', 'Ausonius', 'masculine', 'Latin name/cognomen derived from *Ausonia*, poetic name for Italy (from the Ausones, ancient Italian people). Famous bearer: Decimus Magnus Ausonius (c. 310-395 CE), Roman poet and teacher from Burdigala (Bordeaux), tutor to future Emperor Gratian, consul in 379 CE. His poetry includes *Mosella* (about the Moselle River) and *Ephemeris* (daily routine). The name reflects Italian/Ausonian heritage.', 'Ausonius', 'Ausonius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000380', 'Drusilla', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine cognomen, diminutive form of *Drusus*, meaning "little Drusus" or "of the Drusian line". Famous bearers: Julia Drusilla (16-38 CE), favorite sister of Emperor Caligula, deified after her death; Livia Drusilla (wife of Augustus, mother of Tiberius); Drusilla of Mauretania (daughter of Cleopatra Selene II). The name was popular in the Julio-Claudian dynasty.', 'Drusilla', 'Drusilla', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000381', 'Scribonia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Scribonian family". From the gens Scribonia, possibly derived from *scriba* "scribe, writer". Famous bearer: Scribonia (c. 70 BCE-16 CE), second wife of Augustus (before he married Livia), mother of Julia the Elder. Married Augustus in 40 BCE and was divorced the same day Julia was born (38 BCE). The Scribonii were a distinguished plebeian family.', 'Scribonia', 'Scribonia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000382', 'Fadia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Fadian family". From the gens Fadia, of uncertain etymology. Historical bearer: Fadia, mistress of Mark Antony before his marriages to Fulvia and later to Octavia and Cleopatra. The Fadii were a Roman family, though not among the most prominent patrician houses.', 'Fadia', 'Fadia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000383', 'Fulvia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Fulvian family". From the gens Fulvia, possibly derived from *fulvus* "tawny, yellow, reddish-brown". Famous bearer: Fulvia (c. 83-40 BCE), Roman aristocrat and political activist, wife successively of Publius Clodius Pulcher, Gaius Scribonius Curio, and Mark Antony. First Roman woman to have her face on coins. Known for her involvement in the Perusine War against Octavian.', 'Fulvia', 'Fulvia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000384', 'Tertulla', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine cognomen meaning "little third (daughter)". Diminutive of *Tertia* from *tertius* "third". Used as an affectionate name for third-born daughters or women of the third generation. Historical bearers include members of various Roman families who adopted this cognomen to distinguish family members.', 'Tertulla', 'Tertulla', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000385', 'Terentilla', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine diminutive meaning "little Terentian (woman)". From the nomen Terentius + diminutive suffix *-illa*. Associated with the gens Terentia. The diminutive form suggests affection or indicates a younger or smaller member of the Terentian family. Historical usage in various branches of the Terentii.', 'Terentilla', 'Terentilla', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000386', 'Rufilla', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine cognomen meaning "little red one". Diminutive of *Rufa*, from *rufus* "red, reddish", typically referring to red hair or ruddy complexion. The diminutive form *-illa* adds an affectionate or diminutive quality. Used as a cognomen in various Roman families to distinguish individuals with distinctive coloring.', 'Rufilla', 'Rufilla', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000387', 'Salvia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Salvian family" or derived from *salvus* "safe, healthy, sound". From the gens Salvia. Also related to the herb *salvia* (sage), from *salvere* "to be well, to be in good health". The name conveys wishes for health and well-being. Used by various Roman families as both nomen and cognomen.', 'Salvia', 'Salvia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000388', 'Titisenia', 'feminine', 'Latin feminine nomen meaning "of the Titisenian family". From the gens Titisenia, a Roman family of uncertain etymology. Possibly related to *Titius* or *Titinius* or from Oscan/Sabine origins. Historical bearers include members of the Titisenian family during the late Republic and early Imperial period. A relatively uncommon nomen among Roman families.', 'Titisenia', 'Titisenia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Roman Cognomina (Republican/Imperial Era)
('NA000389', 'Rullianus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen possibly meaning "from Rullae" or related to *rullus*. Most famous bearer: Quintus Fabius Maximus Rullianus, Roman general and consul during the Third Samnite War (326-304 BCE), celebrated for military victories and political leadership. Member of the distinguished gens Fabia.', 'Rullianus', 'Rullianus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000390', 'Verrucosus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning *verrucosus* "warty", "covered with warts". Most famous bearer: Quintus Fabius Maximus Verrucosus "Cunctator" (the Delayer), Roman general and statesman who employed delaying tactics against Hannibal during the Second Punic War. The Fabian strategy of attrition was named after him.', 'Verrucosus', 'Verrucosus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000391', 'Mus', 'masculine', 'Latin cognomen meaning *mus* "mouse". Famous bearers: members of the gens Decia who performed the ritual of *devotio* (self-sacrifice in battle): Publius Decius Mus at the Battle of Sentinum (295 BCE) and his father at the Battle of Vesuvius (340 BCE), both sacrificing themselves to ensure Roman victory.', 'Mus', 'Mus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Roman Nomina
('NA000392', 'Papirius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen of the gens Papiria, one of the most ancient Roman patrician families. Possibly derived from *papyrus* or an Oscan origin. Famous bearers: Lucius Papirius Cursor, legendary general and dictator during the Samnite Wars; Lucius Papirius Praetextatus, known for the story of keeping senatorial secrets from his mother.', 'Papirius', 'Papirius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000393', 'Carvilius', 'masculine', 'Latin nomen of the gens Carvilia, a plebeian family. Etymology uncertain, possibly related to *carvus* or Latin roots. Famous bearer: Spurius Carvilius Maximus Ruga, first Roman to divorce his wife (234 BCE), and established the first fee-charging school in Rome.', 'Carvilius', 'Carvilius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Ligurian Names
('NA000394', 'Curanus', 'masculine', 'Ligurian name, possibly from Celtic or pre-Indo-European substrate. War chief of the Ligurians who fought against Roman expansion in northern Italy during the 2nd century BCE. Etymology uncertain, may be related to Ligurian tribal or personal naming conventions.', 'Curanus', 'Curanus', NULL, NULL, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Virgilian/Mythological Names (Etruscan/Italian)
('NA000395', 'Cupavo', 'masculine', 'Name from Virgil''s *Aeneid*. Etruscan or Italian war chief described as wearing a crest topped with swan plumes. Son of Cycnus, who was transformed into a swan. Led forces from Liguria to aid Aeneas. Name possibly derived from Latin *cuppa* "cup" or Etruscan origin. The swan imagery connects to his father''s mythological transformation.', 'Cupavo', 'Cupavo', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000396', 'Cycnus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name meaning *κύκνος* (*cycnus*) "swan". In Greek mythology, Cycnus was a king of Liguria, son of Sthenelus, and beloved friend (or lover) of Phaethon. After Phaethon''s death, Cycnus grieved and was transformed into a swan by Apollo. Father of Cupavo in Virgil''s *Aeneid*. The name embodies the swan transformation myth.', 'Cycnus', 'Cycnus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000397', 'Phaethon', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Φαέθων* (Phaethōn) meaning "shining one", from *phaethō* "to shine". In Greek mythology, son of Helios (the Sun) who lost control of his father''s sun chariot and was struck down by Zeus to prevent the earth''s destruction. Close friend or lover of Cycnus. The Heliades (his sisters) wept for him and were transformed into poplar trees; their tears became amber.', 'Φαέθων', 'Phaethon', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Etruscan Place Names and Personal Names (from Virgil)
('NA000398', 'Minio', 'masculine', 'Etruscan name, possibly a personal name or toponymic reference. Mentioned in Virgil''s *Aeneid* in the catalogue of Italian forces. Etymology uncertain, may be of Etruscan origin or related to the Minio River (modern Mincio). Context suggests a warrior or leader from Etruria.', 'Minio', 'Minio', NULL, NULL, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000399', 'Pyrgi', 'masculine', 'Latin name derived from the Etruscan port city of Pyrgi (modern Santa Severa), meaning *πύργοι* (pyrgoi) "towers" in Greek. Important harbor of the Etruscan city-state of Caere. Famous for the Pyrgi Tablets, a bilingual Etruscan-Phoenician inscription. In Virgil, represents warriors from this coastal region.', 'Pyrgi', 'Pyrgi', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000400', 'Gravisca', 'feminine', 'Latin name from the Etruscan port city of Gravisca, the harbor of Tarquinia. Name possibly derived from *gravis* "heavy, serious" or Etruscan origin. Important trading port with strong Greek influence. Archaeological site reveals temples to Greek deities. In Virgil''s context, represents forces from this maritime region.', 'Gravisca', 'Gravisca', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000401', 'Ilva', 'feminine', 'Latin name for the island of Elba (*Ilva* in Latin, *Aethalia* in Greek meaning "sooty" from its iron forges). Major source of iron ore in antiquity, essential for Etruscan metalworking. Associated with blacksmiths and the god Vulcan. The island''s rich mineral deposits made it strategically important. Virgil mentions forces from Ilva in the *Aeneid*.', 'Ilva', 'Ilva', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000402', 'Massicus', 'masculine', 'Latin name, possibly Etruscan origin. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, an Etruscan warrior from Tuscany. Name may be related to Mount Massicus in Campania (famous for wine) or Etruscan personal naming. Represents Etruscan forces allied with Aeneas. Etymology uncertain but follows Etruscan naming patterns.', 'Massicus', 'Massicus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000403', 'Abas', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name *Ἄβας* (Abas), possibly meaning "unlucky" or of pre-Greek origin. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, an Etruscan king and warrior from Populonia who brings forces adorned with captured Greek armor. In Greek mythology, also a king of Argos. The name connects Etruscan and Greek traditions.', 'Ἄβας', 'Abas', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000404', 'Populonia', 'feminine', 'Latin name from the Etruscan city of Populonia (Etruscan: *Pupluna* or *Fufluna*, after the god Fufluns). Important coastal city and iron-working center, the only Etruscan city built on the coast. Realm of Abas in Virgil''s *Aeneid*. The name derives from the Etruscan god of wine and vegetation, equivalent to Dionysus/Bacchus.', 'Populonia', 'Populonia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000405', 'Asilas', 'masculine', 'Etruscan name, possibly related to Latin *asylum* or Etruscan roots. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, an Etruscan seer and augur skilled in reading beast entrails (*haruspicy*), interpreting stars (*astrology*), bird cries (*augury*), and lightning (*fulgurology*). Represents the Etruscan religious tradition of divination, for which the Etruscans were famous throughout the ancient world.', 'Asilas', 'Asilas', NULL, NULL, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000406', 'Pisa', 'feminine', 'Latin name from the city of Pisa in Etruria. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, described as a Greek colony founded by colonists from the Greek city of Pisa near the river Alpheus. The Etruscan Pisa was an important city, though its exact founding is legendary. Name possibly derived from Greek *πῖσα* or Etruscan origins. Represents Greek-Etruscan cultural mixing.', 'Pisa', 'Pisa', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000407', 'Astyr', 'masculine', 'Etruscan name of uncertain etymology. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, an Etruscan warrior described as wearing "rainbow-hued" or "star-spangled" (*astris*) armor, suggesting a connection to *astrum* "star". The description emphasizes the renowned Etruscan skill in metalworking and decorated armor. May represent both personal name and poetic epithet.', 'Astyr', 'Astyr', NULL, NULL, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000408', 'Ocnus', 'masculine', 'Latin/Etruscan name *Ocnus* (also *Bianor*), possibly meaning "hesitant" from *ocnos* "hesitation". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, son of the prophetess Manto and the Tuscan river god Tiber. Legendary founder of Mantua, named after his mother. Represents the mythological foundation of the city and connection between Etruscan and Greek prophetic traditions.', 'Ocnus', 'Ocnus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000409', 'Mincius', 'masculine', 'Latin name of the river Mincio (*Mincius*), tributary of the Po. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, personified as son of the god Benacus (Lake Garda). The river flows through Mantua, Virgil''s birthplace, giving it special significance in his work. Name possibly of pre-Indo-European or Etruscan origin. Represents river deity and local geography.', 'Mincius', 'Mincius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000410', 'Aulestes', 'masculine', 'Greek/Etruscan name, possibly meaning "flute player" from Greek *αὐλητής* (aulētēs). In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, an Etruscan commander who captains the mighty warship named Triton. The name combines Greek musical terminology with Etruscan military leadership, reflecting cultural exchange. Represents Etruscan naval power and Greek cultural influence.', 'Aulestes', 'Aulestes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Sea Nymphs (from Virgil)
('NA000411', 'Cybebe', 'feminine', 'Latin name from Greek *Κυβέβη* (Kybebē), related to Cybele. In Virgil''s *Aeneid* (Book 10), a sea nymph created when the goddess Cybele transformed Aeneas'' burning fleet into sea nymphs to save them from Turnus. The name connects to the Phrygian mother goddess Cybele, from whose sacred grove on Mount Ida the ships were built.', 'Cybebe', 'Cybebe', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000412', 'Cymodocea', 'feminine', 'Greek name *Κυμοδόκεια* (Kymodocea) meaning "wave-receiver", from *kyma* (κῦμα) "wave" and *dechomai* (δέχομαι) "to receive". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, the most eloquent of the sea nymphs born from Aeneas'' transformed fleet. She warns Aeneas of Turnus'' attack. In Greek mythology, also a Nereid. The name embodies the sea''s gentle, receiving nature.', 'Κυμοδόκεια', 'Cymodocea', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Cult Places of Venus/Aphrodite
('NA000413', 'Paphus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name *Πάφος* (Paphos), from the city of Paphos in Cyprus, sacred to Aphrodite/Venus. Legendary son of Pygmalion and Galatea, founder of the city. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, one of Venus'' sacred cult centers. The name represents the goddess'' worship site where she was born from sea foam. Also used as masculine personal name in antiquity.', 'Πάφος', 'Paphus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000414', 'Idalia', 'feminine', 'Latin/Greek name from Mount Idalium in Cyprus, another sacred site of Aphrodite/Venus. From *Ἰδάλιον* (Idalion), meaning uncertain, possibly pre-Greek. Poetic epithet of Venus (*Venus Idalia*). In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, used to invoke the goddess by her cult location. The name evokes Venus'' sacred groves and worship in Cyprus.', 'Idalia', 'Idalia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000415', 'Cythera', 'feminine', 'Greek/Latin name *Κύθηρα* (Kythēra), from the island of Cythera (modern Kythira) between Crete and the Peloponnese, sacred to Aphrodite/Venus. According to myth, the foam from which Aphrodite was born first touched land here. Poetic epithet: *Venus Cytherea*. In Virgil''s works, used to invoke Venus by her birth-place. Name possibly pre-Greek in origin.', 'Κύθηρα', 'Cythera', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Trojan Names (from Virgil)
('NA000416', 'Asius', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name *Ἄσιος* (Asios), possibly meaning "from Asia" or related to the region of Asia Minor. In Homer''s *Iliad* and Virgil''s *Aeneid*, a Trojan warrior, son of Imbrasus. Brother of Thymoetes. Represents Trojan forces and connections to Asia Minor. Multiple figures in Greek mythology bear this name, typically associated with Trojan or Asian lineages.', 'Ἄσιος', 'Asius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000417', 'Thymoetes', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Θυμοίτης* (Thymoitēs), possibly meaning "spirited" or "passionate", from *thymos* (θυμός) "spirit, courage, passion". In Virgil''s *Aeneid* and Trojan legend, son of Hicetaon, Trojan elder who advocated bringing the Trojan Horse into the city. Brother of Asius. The name reflects the emotional intensity associated with the character.', 'Θυμοίτης', 'Thymoetes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000418', 'Assaracus', 'masculine', 'Greek/Latin name *Ἀσσάρακος* (Assarakos), of uncertain etymology, possibly Anatolian or pre-Greek. In Greek and Roman mythology, son of Tros, brother of Ilus and Ganymede, ancestor of the Trojan royal line. Great-grandfather of Aeneas through his son Capys. The gens Iulia claimed descent through this lineage. Important in establishing Rome''s Trojan ancestry.', 'Ἀσσάρακος', 'Assaracus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000419', 'Castor', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Κάστωρ* (Kastōr), possibly meaning "beaver" or "he who excels". One of the Dioscuri (twin sons of Zeus), brother of Pollux (Polydeuces). Renowned horseman and warrior. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, invoked as protector of sailors and cavalry. Worshipped in Rome at the Temple of Castor and Pollux in the Forum. Patron of Roman equestrian class.', 'Κάστωρ', 'Castor', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000420', 'Thymbus', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Θύμβος* (Thymbos), possibly meaning "burial mound" or related to *thymos* "spirit". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, a Trojan warrior. The name may also connect to the Thymbraean Apollo, worshipped in Thymbra near Troy. Represents Trojan forces and local Trojan topography and cult practice.', 'Θύμβος', 'Thymbus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- Lycian Names (from Virgil)
('NA000421', 'Clarus', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning *clarus* "bright, clear, famous, renowned". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, a Lycian warrior allied with the Trojans. Lycians were close allies of Troy in the Trojan War. The name, while Latin in form, may represent a Latinized version of a Lycian name, or simply means "the famous one". Killed in battle in the *Aeneid*.', 'Clarus', 'Clarus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000422', 'Thaemon', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Θαίμων* (Thaimōn), possibly related to *thauma* (θαῦμα) "wonder, marvel" or *thymos* "spirit". In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, a Lycian warrior fighting alongside the Trojans. Lycians were renowned archers and close allies of Troy. The name represents the Lycian-Trojan alliance and Asia Minor martial traditions.', 'Θαίμων', 'Thaemon', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000423', 'Haemon', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Αἵμων* (Haimōn) meaning "bloody" from *haima* (αἷμα) "blood". In Greek mythology, multiple figures bear this name, including the son of Creon who loved Antigone. In some traditions, a companion of Aeneas. The name evokes martial prowess and the blood of battle or bloodline. Common name in Greek epic and tragedy.', 'Αἵμων', 'Haemon', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000424', 'Acmon', 'masculine', 'Greek name *Ἄκμων* (Akmōn) meaning "anvil", from the root *ak-* "sharp, pointed". In Greek mythology, one of the Cyclopes who forged Zeus'' thunderbolts. In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, a companion of Aeneas from Troy. The name connects to metalworking, blacksmithing, and the forging of weapons. Symbolizes strength and craftmanship.', 'Ἄκμων', 'Acmon', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000425', 'Oricia', 'feminine', 'Latin/Greek name, possibly from *Ὠρίκια* (Ōrikia) or related to *hora* "season, time" or the Horae (goddesses of seasons). In Virgil''s *Aeneid*, mentioned in the context of Trojan or Italian allies. Etymology uncertain, may be topographic (from a place name) or personal. The name suggests connection to time, seasons, or a specific locale.', 'Oricia', 'Oricia', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- ============================================================================
-- BATCH 1: GREEK PHILOSOPHERS (12 names)
-- Added: 2025-11-09
-- IDs: NA000426-NA000437
-- ============================================================================

('NA000426', 'Θαλῆς', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "bloom, flourish". Pre-Socratic philosopher from Miletus (c. 624-546 BCE), considered the first Greek philosopher. Proposed water as the fundamental substance (arche) of all things.', 'Θαλῆς', 'Thales', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000427', 'Ἀναξίμανδρος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "lord of men, ruler of men" from ἀναξ (lord, master) + ἀνήρ (man). Pre-Socratic philosopher from Miletus (c. 610-546 BCE), student of Thales. Introduced the concept of the apeiron (the boundless/infinite) as the origin of all things. Created early maps and astronomical models.', 'Ἀναξίμανδρος', 'Anaximander', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000428', 'Ἀναξιμένης', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "lord of strength, master of might" from ἀναξι- (lord, master) + -μένης (strength, might from μένος). Pre-Socratic philosopher from Miletus (c. 586-526 BCE), student of Anaximander. Proposed air (aer) as the fundamental substance. Explained change through rarefaction and condensation.', 'Ἀναξιμένης', 'Anaximenes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000429', 'Ἀναξαγόρας', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "lord of the assembly, master of the marketplace" from ἀναξ (lord) + ἀγορά (assembly, marketplace). Pre-Socratic philosopher from Clazomenae (c. 500-428 BCE). Introduced the concept of Nous (mind/intellect) as the ordering principle of the cosmos. Proposed that everything contains a portion of everything else.', 'Ἀναξαγόρας', 'Anaxagoras', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000430', 'Παρμενίδης', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "steadfast, enduring". Pre-Socratic philosopher from Elea (c. 515-450 BCE). Founder of the Eleatic school. Argued for monism and the unchanging nature of reality in his philosophical poem "On Nature". Distinguished between the "Way of Truth" and "Way of Opinion".', 'Παρμενίδης', 'Parmenides', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000431', 'Πρωταγόρας', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "first in the assembly, chief speaker" from πρῶτος (first, foremost) + ἀγορά (assembly). Leading Sophist philosopher from Abdera (c. 490-420 BCE). Famous for the statement "Man is the measure of all things". Developed theories of relativism and taught rhetoric and virtue.', 'Πρωταγόρας', 'Protagoras', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000432', 'Ἀντισθένης', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "opposing strength, counter-force" from ἀντί (against, opposite) + σθένος (strength, might). Greek philosopher (c. 445-365 BCE), founder of Cynic philosophy. Student of Socrates, teacher of Diogenes. Emphasized self-sufficiency (autarkeia) and living according to nature. Rejected conventional values and social norms.', 'Ἀντισθένης', 'Antisthenes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000433', 'Σπεύσιππος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "hastening horse, eager horse" from σπεύδω (hasten, be eager) + ἵππος (horse). Greek philosopher (c. 407-339 BCE), nephew of Plato. Succeeded Plato as head of the Academy. Developed mathematical and ontological theories, emphasizing the importance of numbers and mathematical objects.', 'Σπεύσιππος', 'Speusippus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000434', 'Ξενοκράτης', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "foreign power, strength of the stranger" from ξένος (stranger, foreigner) + κράτος (power, strength). Greek philosopher (c. 396-314 BCE), student of Plato. Succeeded Speusippus as head of the Academy (339-314 BCE). Developed tripartite division of philosophy and theories on daemons and the soul.', 'Ξενοκράτης', 'Xenocrates', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000435', 'Ἡρακλείδης', 'masculine', 'Greek patronymic name meaning "descendant of Heracles, son of Heracles". Heraclides Ponticus (c. 390-310 BCE), Greek philosopher and astronomer from Heraclea Pontika. Student of Plato and associate of Aristotle. Proposed that Earth rotates on its axis and that Mercury and Venus orbit the Sun.', 'Ἡρακλείδης', 'Heraclides', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000436', 'Θεόφραστος', 'masculine', 'Greek theophoric compound name meaning "god-speaker, divinely eloquent" from θεός (god) + φράζω (speak, tell). Greek philosopher (c. 371-287 BCE), successor of Aristotle as head of the Lyceum. Made significant contributions to botany, biology, ethics, and logic. Original name was Tyrtamus; renamed by Aristotle for his eloquence.', 'Θεόφραστος', 'Theophrastus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000437', 'Στράτων', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "army, military expedition". Strato of Lampsacus (c. 335-269 BCE), Greek philosopher who succeeded Theophrastus as head of the Lyceum. Known as "The Physicist" for his materialist approach and experimental methods in natural philosophy. Rejected teleology in favor of mechanical causation.', 'Στράτων', 'Strato', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- ============================================================================
-- BATCH 2: ROMAN NAMES & STOIC PHILOSOPHERS (13 names)
-- IDs: NA000438-NA000450
-- ============================================================================

('NA000438', 'Ζήνων', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "of Zeus, gift of Zeus". Zeno of Citium (c. 334-262 BCE), founder of Stoic philosophy. Born in Cyprus, studied under Crates the Cynic. Established his school at the Stoa Poikile (Painted Porch) in Athens. Taught logic, physics, and ethics centered on living according to nature and reason.', 'Ζήνων', 'Zenon', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000439', 'Κλεάνθης', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "glorious flower, blooming fame" from κλέος (glory, fame) + ἄνθος (flower, bloom). Cleanthes of Assos (c. 330-230 BCE), second head of the Stoic school after Zeno. Known for his "Hymn to Zeus" and emphasis on divine providence. Worked as a water-carrier at night to fund his philosophical studies.', 'Κλεάνθης', 'Cleanthes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000440', 'Χρύσιππος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "golden horse" from χρυσός (gold) + ἵππος (horse). Chrysippus of Soli (c. 279-206 BCE), third head of the Stoic school. Most prolific Stoic writer with over 700 works. Systematized Stoic logic and ethics. Famous saying: "Without Chrysippus, there would be no Stoa."', 'Χρύσιππος', 'Chrysippus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000441', 'Iunius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name (gens Iunia) meaning "of Juno, sacred to Juno; June-born". Associated with the goddess Juno and the month of June. Famous bearers include Lucius Junius Brutus (founder of the Roman Republic) and Marcus Junius Brutus (Caesar''s assassin).', 'Iunius', 'Iunius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000442', 'Ennius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name, possibly from Oscan origin. Quintus Ennius (c. 239-169 BCE), Roman poet known as the "father of Roman poetry". Introduced Greek hexameter to Latin literature. Wrote the epic "Annales" chronicling Roman history. Coined phrase "O Tite tute Tati tibi tanta tyranne tulisti".', 'Ennius', 'Ennius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000443', 'Roscius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name meaning "of the dew, dewy; possibly rose-related". Most famous bearer: Quintus Roscius Gallus (c. 126-62 BCE), greatest Roman comic actor. So renowned that "Roscius" became synonymous with excellence in acting. Defended by Cicero in "Pro Roscio Comoedo".', 'Roscius', 'Roscius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000444', 'Fabius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name (gens Fabia) meaning "bean-grower, bean-related" from *faba* (bean). One of the most ancient and distinguished patrician families. Notable bearer: Quintus Fabius Maximus Verrucosus "Cunctator" (the Delayer), who used attrition warfare against Hannibal.', 'Fabius', 'Fabius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000445', 'Naevius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name from *naevus* (mole, birthmark) meaning "having moles or birthmarks". Gnaeus Naevius (c. 270-201 BCE) was an early Roman epic poet and dramatist who wrote the "Bellum Punicum" about the First Punic War. Imprisoned for criticizing the Metelli family.', 'Naevius', 'Naevius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000446', 'Livius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name (gens Livia) meaning "bluish, envious; possibly from Etruscan". Famous bearers include Livius Andronicus (c. 284-205 BCE), first Roman literary figure who translated Homer''s Odyssey into Latin; and Titus Livius (59 BCE-17 CE), historian who wrote "Ab Urbe Condita".', 'Livius', 'Livius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000447', 'Pacuvius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name from *pax* (peace) meaning "peaceful, peace-loving". Marcus Pacuvius (c. 220-130 BCE) was Rome''s greatest tragic poet before Accius. Nephew of Ennius. Known for complex plots and innovative language. Only fragments of his works survive.', 'Pacuvius', 'Pacuvius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000448', 'Accius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name, possibly from Oscan or Umbrian origin. Lucius Accius (c. 170-86 BCE) was Rome''s greatest tragic dramatist. Known for powerful language and innovative staging. Famous quote: "Oderint dum metuant" (Let them hate, so long as they fear). Influenced later Roman drama.', 'Accius', 'Accius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000449', 'Caecilius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name from *caecus* (blind) meaning "blind, dim-sighted". Caecilius Statius (c. 220-168 BCE) was Rome''s leading comic playwright between Plautus and Terence. Born in Gaul as an Insubrian Celt, came to Rome as a slave. Adapted Greek New Comedy for Roman audiences.', 'Caecilius', 'Caecilius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000450', 'Afranius', 'masculine', 'Roman family name, possibly from place name or ethnic origin. Lucius Afranius (c. 150-90 BCE) was the leading writer of fabulae togatae (comedies about Roman life, as opposed to Greek-set palliatae). Depicted everyday Roman customs and social situations. Contemporary with Accius.', 'Afranius', 'Afranius', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- ============================================================================
-- BATCH 3: GREEK POETS & LYRICISTS (10 names)
-- IDs: NA000454-NA000463
-- ============================================================================

('NA000451', 'Ἀλκαῖος', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "strength, might". Alcaeus of Mytilene (c. 620-580 BCE), Greek lyric poet from Lesbos. Contemporary and possible lover of Sappho. Known for drinking songs, hymns, political poetry. Invented the Alcaic stanza. Only fragments survive. Horace admired and imitated his work.', 'Ἀλκαῖος', 'Alcaeus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000452', 'Σιμωνίδης', 'masculine', 'Greek patronymic name meaning "son of Simonos; flat-nosed". Simonides of Ceos (c. 556-468 BCE), Greek lyric poet. Master of epigrams, including epitaph for Spartans at Thermopylae: "Go tell the Spartans...". Credited with inventing mnemonic techniques. Won numerous poetry competitions. Uncle of Bacchylides.', 'Σιμωνίδης', 'Simonides', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000453', 'Ἀρχίλοχος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "leader of an ambush, commander of a company" from ἀρχή (beginning, rule, leadership) + λόχος (ambush, company of soldiers). Archilochus of Paros (c. 680-645 BCE), Greek iambic and elegiac poet. Among the earliest known Greek lyric poets. Famous for satirical and realistic poetry. Soldier and mercenary.', 'Ἀρχίλοχος', 'Archilochus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000454', 'Ἀλκμάν', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "mighty strength, strong power". Alcman of Sparta (c. 7th century BCE), Greek choral lyric poet. Possibly from Lydia originally. Composed partheneia (maiden songs) for Spartan girls'' choirs. Known for vivid natural imagery and references to Spartan customs. Major fragments discovered in Egyptian papyri.', 'Ἀλκμάν', 'Alcman', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000455', 'Βακχυλίδης', 'masculine', 'Greek theophoric compound name meaning "descendant of Bacchus, son of Bacchus" from Βάκχος (Bacchus) + -ίδης (patronymic suffix). Bacchylides of Ceos (c. 518-451 BCE), Greek lyric poet. Nephew and rival of Simonides. Composed epinicians (victory odes) and dithyrambs. Contemporary and rival of Pindar. Much of his work rediscovered in Egyptian papyri in 1896.', 'Βακχυλίδης', 'Bacchylides', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000456', 'Στησίχορος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "establisher of choruses, chorus-setter" from ἵστημι (to set up, establish) + χορός (chorus, dance). Stesichorus of Himera (c. 630-555 BCE), Greek lyric poet from Sicily. Real name Tisias; "Stesichorus" was a nickname. Known for narrative lyric poetry on mythological themes. Said to have been blinded for insulting Helen, then cured when he recanted.', 'Στησίχορος', 'Stesichorus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000457', 'Ἴβυκος', 'masculine', 'Greek name, etymology uncertain, possibly pre-Greek. Ibycus of Rhegium (c. 6th century BCE), Greek lyric poet from southern Italy. Known for love poetry and mythological narratives. Contemporary of Anacreon. Famous legend: murdered by robbers, cranes overhead witnessed the crime and later revealed the killers ("Cranes of Ibycus").', 'Ἴβυκος', 'Ibycus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000458', 'Μίμνερμος', 'masculine', 'Greek name, etymology uncertain, possibly "remembering contest/strife". Mimnermus of Colophon (c. 630-600 BCE), Greek elegiac poet. Known for love poetry and laments on the brevity of youth. Composed "Nanno" named after a flute-girl he loved. Influenced later Roman elegiac poets. Only fragments survive.', 'Μίμνερμος', 'Mimnermus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000459', 'Τυρταῖος', 'masculine', 'Greek name, etymology uncertain, possibly related to Tyrrhenian. Tyrtaeus of Sparta (c. 7th century BCE), Greek elegiac poet. Possibly Athenian sent to Sparta as general. Wrote martial elegies to inspire Spartans during Second Messenian War. Emphasized civic duty, honor, and courage in battle. His poems were sung by Spartan armies on campaign.', 'Τυρταῖος', 'Tyrtaeus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000460', 'Θέογνις', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "born of gods, god-born". Theognis of Megara (c. 570-485 BCE), Greek elegiac poet. Known for didactic poetry addressed to young Cyrnus. Over 1,400 lines survive (though some may be by other poets). Aristocratic perspective, lamenting social changes. Themes: friendship, love, politics, morality.', 'Θέογνις', 'Theognis', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- ============================================================================
-- BATCH 4: DEITIES & MYTHOLOGICAL FIGURES (11 names)
-- IDs: NA000464-NA000474
-- ============================================================================

('NA000461', 'Ὀρφεύς', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "darkness, night; possibly Thracian origin". Legendary Greek poet and musician, son of Apollo (or Oeagrus) and Calliope. Central figure in Orphic mysteries. Famous for journey to underworld to retrieve wife Eurydice. His music could charm all living things. Torn apart by Maenads. Founder of Orphism religious tradition.', 'Ὀρφεύς', 'Orpheus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000462', 'Juventas', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "youth, youthfulness". Roman goddess of youth, equivalent to Greek Hebe. Daughter of Jupiter and Juno. Protector of young men, especially as they assumed the toga virilis. Had temple on Capitoline Hill. Invoked when young soldiers took military oath.', 'Juventas', 'Juventas', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000463', 'Portunus', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning "harbor, port; doorway". Ancient Roman god of keys, doors, livestock, and harbors. Associated with portus (harbor). Festival Portunalia celebrated August 17. Temple near Forum Boarium. Later assimilated to Greek Palaemon. Protected keys and gates, guardian of doorways.', 'Portunus', 'Portunus', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000464', 'Penates', 'masculine', 'Latin name meaning "of the storeroom, pantry gods". Roman household deities protecting the home''s storeroom (penus). Worshipped alongside Lares and Vesta. State cult of Penates Publici protected Roman state. Aeneas brought Trojan Penates to Italy. Represented continuity of family and state.', 'Penates', 'Penates', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000465', 'Fortuna', 'feminine', 'Latin name meaning "luck, chance, fortune". Roman goddess of fortune and personification of luck. Equivalent to Greek Tyche. Depicted with cornucopia, ship''s rudder, and wheel. Multiple cult titles: Fortuna Redux (safe return), Fortuna Primigenia (firstborn). Major cult center at Praeneste. Symbol of fate''s fickleness.', 'Fortuna', 'Fortuna', 'RR00001', 'SC00001', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000466', 'Μήδεια', 'feminine', 'Greek name meaning "cunning, planning, counsel". Princess of Colchis, daughter of King Aeëtes and granddaughter of Helios. Sorceress who helped Jason obtain Golden Fleece. Murdered her brother Apsyrtus and later her own children in revenge against Jason. Subject of Euripides'' tragedy. Symbol of wronged woman''s vengeance.', 'Μήδεια', 'Medea', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000467', 'Τυνδάρεως', 'masculine', 'Greek name, etymology uncertain, possibly pre-Greek. King of Sparta, husband of Leda. Mortal father of Clytemnestra and Helen (whose divine father was Zeus). Father of Castor and Pollux (Dioscuri). Administered oath to Helen''s suitors, leading to Trojan War. Restored to throne by Heracles after being deposed.', 'Τυνδάρεως', 'Tyndareus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000468', 'Ἰνώ', 'feminine', 'Greek name, possibly related to strong, sinew. Daughter of Cadmus and Harmonia, sister of Semele. Raised infant Dionysus, incurring Hera''s wrath. Driven mad, leapt into sea with son Melicertes. Transformed into sea goddess Leucothea ("White Goddess"). Rescued Odysseus. Roman equivalent: Mater Matuta.', 'Ἰνώ', 'Ino', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000469', 'Καρνεάδης', 'masculine', 'Greek patronymic name, possibly related to Carneia festival or horn. Carneades of Cyrene (c. 214-129 BCE), founder of Third/New Academy. Leading Academic skeptic philosopher. Famous for arguing both sides of any question with equal persuasiveness. Part of philosophical embassy to Rome (155 BCE) with Diogenes and Critolaus. Influenced later skepticism.', 'Καρνεάδης', 'Carneades', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000470', 'Παναίτιος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "all-causing, universal cause" from πᾶν (all, every) + αἰτία (cause, reason). Panaetius of Rhodes (c. 185-110 BCE), Stoic philosopher. Scholarch of Stoic school. Introduced Stoicism to Rome through Scipionic Circle. Modified orthodox Stoicism, making it more practical and Roman. Teacher of Posidonius. Major influence on Cicero''s "De Officiis".', 'Παναίτιος', 'Panaetius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000471', 'Ποσειδώνιος', 'masculine', 'Greek theophoric name meaning "of Poseidon, gift of Poseidon". Posidonius of Apameia (c. 135-51 BCE), Stoic philosopher, historian, geographer, and polymath. Student of Panaetius. Established school in Rhodes. Combined Stoicism with Platonism. Wrote on physics, meteorology, geography, history, ethics. Influenced Cicero and Pompey. Calculated Earth''s circumference.', 'Ποσειδώνιος', 'Posidonius', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

-- ============================================================================
-- BATCH 5: REMAINING PHILOSOPHERS & MISCELLANEOUS (12 names)
-- IDs: NA000472-NA000483
