('NA000472', 'Δικαίαρχος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "just ruler, righteous leader" from δίκαιος (just, righteous) + ἀρχός (ruler, leader). Dicaearchus of Messana (c. 350-285 BCE), Greek Peripatetic philosopher. Student of Aristotle, contemporary of Theophrastus. Wrote on geography, political philosophy, biography, cultural history. Work "Life of Greece" traced Greek civilization. Calculated heights of Greek mountains.', 'Δικαίαρχος', 'Dicaearchus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000473', 'Ἀριστόξενος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "best guest, excellent stranger" from ἄριστος (best, excellent) + ξένος (stranger, guest). Aristoxenus of Tarentum (c. 375-300 BCE), Greek Peripatetic philosopher and music theorist. Student of Aristotle. Wrote "Elements of Harmony" - first systematic Greek musical treatise. Also wrote on biography, education, politics. Disappointed when Theophrastus chosen over him to lead Lyceum.', 'Ἀριστόξενος', 'Aristoxenus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000474', 'Κλέαρχος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "glorious ruler, famous leader" from κλέος (glory, fame) + ἀρχός (ruler). Clearchus of Soli (c. 4th-3rd century BCE), Greek Peripatetic philosopher. Student of Aristotle. Wrote on various topics including biography, proverbs, love, sleep. Work on India discussed Indian philosophy. Described Jewish people as "philosophers by race". Only fragments survive.', 'Κλέαρχος', 'Clearchus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000475', 'Λύκων', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "wolf, wolf-like". Lyco of Troas (c. 299-225 BCE), Greek Peripatetic philosopher. Third successor of Aristotle as head of Lyceum after Strato. Known more for eloquence and teaching ability than original philosophical contributions. Led school for 44 years. Emphasized ethical education of youth.', 'Λύκων', 'Lyco', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000476', 'Κράντωρ', 'masculine', 'Greek name, possibly meaning "accomplisher, fulfiller". Crantor of Soli (c. 335-275 BCE), Greek Academic philosopher. First commentator on Plato, wrote on "Timaeus". Work "On Grief" was influential consolatory treatise. Contemporary of Arcesilaus and Polemo. Teacher of Arcesilaus. Cicero praised his eloquence.', 'Κράντωρ', 'Crantor', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000477', 'Πολέμων', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "war, battle; warlike". Polemo of Athens (c. 350-270 BCE), Greek Academic philosopher. Student and successor of Xenocrates as head of Academy. Legendary conversion from dissolute youth to philosophy. Emphasized ethics over dialectics. Teacher of Crates of Athens and Crantor. Influenced Zeno and early Stoicism.', 'Πολέμων', 'Polemo', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000478', 'Κράτης', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "power, strength, might". Crates of Athens (c. 4th-3rd century BCE), Greek Academic philosopher. Student of Polemo, succeeded him as head of Academy. Teacher of Arcesilaus. Little known of his work. Distinguished from Crates of Thebes (Cynic) and Crates of Mallos (grammarian).', 'Κράτης', 'Crates', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000479', 'Ἀρκεσίλαος', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "defender of the people, sufficient for the people" from ἀρκέω (ward off, defend, suffice) + λαός (people). Arcesilaus of Pitane (c. 316-241 BCE), Greek philosopher who founded Academic Skepticism (Middle Academy). Rejected Stoic epistemology. Argued for suspension of judgment (epochē). Influenced by Socratic method and Pyrrhonian skepticism. Taught orally, wrote nothing.', 'Ἀρκεσίλαος', 'Arcesilaus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000480', 'Λακύδης', 'masculine', 'Greek name, etymology uncertain, possibly from Laconia. Lacydes of Cyrene (c. 3rd century BCE), Greek Academic Skeptic philosopher. Succeeded Arcesilaus as head of Academy. Continued skeptical tradition. Split Academy into two schools (himself and Telecles/Evander). Resigned due to old age. Little known of his specific teachings.', 'Λακύδης', 'Lacydes', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000481', 'Τηλεκλῆς', 'masculine', 'Greek compound name meaning "far-famed, renowned from afar" from τῆλε (far, afar) + κλέος (glory, fame). Telecles of Phocaea (c. 3rd century BCE), Greek Academic Skeptic philosopher. Along with Evander, co-head of Academy after Lacydes. Split indicated internal divisions in skeptical Academy. Continued Academic Skeptical tradition. Few details of his life or teachings survive.', 'Τηλεκλῆς', 'Telecles', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000482', 'Εὔανδρος', 'masculine', 'Greek name meaning "good man, manly, brave". Evander of Phocaea (c. 3rd century BCE), Greek Academic Skeptic philosopher. Co-head of Academy with Telecles after Lacydes. Minimal information survives about his specific philosophical positions. Represented continuation of skeptical Academy tradition during period of fragmentation.', 'Εὔανδρος', 'Evander', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP),

('NA000483', 'Ἡγησῖνος', 'masculine', 'Greek name related to leadership, guidance. Hegesinus of Pergamon (c. 3rd-2nd century BCE), Greek Academic Skeptic philosopher. Succeeded Telecles and Evander as head of Academy. Reunified the divided Academy. Teacher of Carneades. Continued skeptical tradition between Middle and New Academy periods. Bridge figure in Academic development.', 'Ἡγησῖνος', 'Hegesinus', 'RR00004', 'SC00002', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP);